This paper deals with learning dynamics models for model-based reinforcement learning in the context of contact-rich manipulation tasks. The paper focuses on a solution that supports discontinuous state evolution caused by impacting conditions. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses probabilistic models and long-term prediction, which are common topics in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also deals with system dynamics, which is a topic in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its method on a motion task, which suggests that it may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
